Synchronization & Deadlocks

1) What is synchronization in Java & why is synchronization needed?
-->Synchronization is the process of allowing only one thread at a time to access a shared resource or critical section.
    
    Need for synchronization:
        Prevents data inconsistency
        Avoids race conditions
        Maintains thread safety
        Ensures proper execution of shared resources


2) What is the difference between synchronized method and synchronized block?
-->
| Synchronized Method           | Synchronized Block                  |
| ----------------------------- | ----------------------------------- |
| Entire method is synchronized | Only specific block is synchronized |
| Locks complete method         | Locks only selected code            |
| Lower performance             | Better performance                  |
| Simple to use                 | More flexible                       |

  Example:
    Synchronized Method
    synchronized void display() {
        System.out.println("Method");
    }
    Synchronized Block
    void display() {
    
        synchronized(this) {
            System.out.println("Block");
        }
    }


3) What is the lock object in synchronization?
-->A lock object is the object whose monitor lock is used by a thread to enter a synchronized method or block.

    Only one thread can hold the lock at a time.
    
    Example:
        synchronized(this) {
        
        }
        
        Here:
          this is the lock object.



4) What is static synchronization? Difference between object level synchronization & class level synchronization? How to implement both?
-->Static Synchronization:
      Static synchronization locks the class object instead of individual objects.
      
      Used when static data is shared among all objects.

| Object Level Synchronization                 | Class Level Synchronization      |
| -------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------- |
| Locks object                                 | Locks class                      |
| Different objects can execute simultaneously | Only one thread for entire class |
| Uses non-static synchronized methods         | Uses static synchronized methods |


Object Level Synchronization:
      synchronized void show() {
      
      }
Class Level Synchronization:
      static synchronized void show() {
      
      }



5) What is a deadlock, how to implement it & how can you avoid it?
-->Deadlock is a situation where two or more threads wait forever for each other’s resources.

Deadlock Example
class Test {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        String resource1 = "Java";
        String resource2 = "Python";

        Thread t1 = new Thread() {

            public void run() {

                synchronized(resource1) {

                    synchronized(resource2) {

                        System.out.println("Thread 1");
                    }
                }
            }
        };

        Thread t2 = new Thread() {

            public void run() {

                synchronized(resource2) {

                    synchronized(resource1) {

                        System.out.println("Thread 2");
                    }
                }
            }
        };

        t1.start();
        t2.start();
    }
}
    How to avoid deadlock:
        Maintain proper lock order
        Avoid nested locks
        Use timeout mechanisms
        Minimize synchronized blocks
